            <!-- Explanations -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is a carbon footprint?</h2>
              <p>
                A <strong>carbon footprint</strong> is the total amount of
                greenhouse gases (GHGs) emitted directly and indirectly by a
                person, organization, product, or activity. It is usually
                expressed in
                <strong>tons of CO₂ equivalent (tCO₂e) per year</strong>, which
                combines carbon dioxide (CO₂), methane (CH₄), nitrous oxide
                (N₂O), and other gases into a single metric based on their
                global warming potential.
              </p>
              <p>
                For an individual, a carbon footprint typically includes
                emissions from:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Home energy</strong> – electricity, heating, cooling,
                  cooking.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transport</strong> – car use, public transit, flights.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Food</strong> – production, processing, and transport
                  of what you eat.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Goods & services</strong> – clothes, electronics,
                  leisure, healthcare, digital services, etc.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How this carbon footprint calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool provides a
                <strong>transparent, category-based estimate</strong> of your
                annual emissions. It uses published emission factors and simple
                formulas so you can see how each input affects your total.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Home energy</h3>
              <p>
                Home energy emissions are calculated from your annual energy use
                and the carbon intensity of each fuel.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Electricity</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Electricity emissions (kg CO₂e)} = \text{kWh per
                  year} \times \text{grid emission factor (kg CO₂e/kWh)} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Natural gas</strong> (using ≈ 5.3 kg CO₂e/therm):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Gas emissions (kg CO₂e)} = \text{therms per year}
                  \times 5.3 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Heating oil</strong> (using ≈ 2.68 kg CO₂e/liter):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Oil emissions (kg CO₂e)} = \text{liters per year}
                  \times 2.68 \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Other heating fuels are converted using a generic factor of ≈
                0.25 kg CO₂e/kWh unless you specify a more precise value.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Transport & travel</h3>
              <p>
                For car travel, the calculator uses your annual distance and
                fuel economy to estimate fuel burned, then multiplies by a
                fuel-specific emission factor.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Car fuel use</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Liters per year} = \dfrac{\text{km per year} \times
                  \text{L/100 km}}{100} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Car emissions</strong> (gasoline example, ≈ 2.31 kg
                  CO₂e/L):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Car emissions (kg CO₂e)} = \text{liters per year}
                  \times 2.31 \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Diesel and hybrid vehicles use slightly different factors.
                Electric vehicles use your electricity emission factor and an
                assumed consumption per km.
              </p>
              <p>
                Public transport emissions are estimated with average
                per-kilometer factors (e.g. bus ≈ 0.1 kg CO₂e/km, rail ≈ 0.04 kg
                CO₂e/km).
              </p>
              <p>
                Flights are a major contributor for many people. We use typical
                per-flight averages that include a
                <strong>radiative forcing uplift</strong> to account for
                high-altitude effects:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Short-haul (&lt; 3h): ≈ 0.3 tCO₂e per one-way flight.</li>
                <li>Medium-haul (3–6h): ≈ 0.6 tCO₂e per one-way flight.</li>
                <li>Long-haul (&gt; 6h): ≈ 1.6 tCO₂e per one-way flight.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Food & diet</h3>
              <p>
                Food emissions are estimated using life-cycle assessments of
                typical diets. Instead of asking for every ingredient, we use
                <strong>diet archetypes</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>High meat: ≈ 4.5–5.5 tCO₂e/person/year</li>
                <li>Average omnivore: ≈ 3–4 tCO₂e/person/year</li>
                <li>Low meat: ≈ 2.5–3 tCO₂e/person/year</li>
                <li>Vegetarian: ≈ 1.7–2.5 tCO₂e/person/year</li>
                <li>Vegan: ≈ 1.3–2.0 tCO₂e/person/year</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These values are then adjusted up or down based on your
                self-reported food waste level.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Goods, services & lifestyle</h3>
              <p>
                Emissions from goods and services are harder to measure
                directly, so we use
                <strong>consumption-based averages</strong> from national
                footprint studies. Your selections (low/average/high) scale a
                baseline value per person.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting your carbon footprint</h2>
              <p>
                Once you click <strong>“Calculate footprint”</strong>, you will
                see:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your <strong>total annual footprint</strong> in tCO₂e.</li>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>per-person footprint</strong> (total divided by
                  household size).
                </li>
                <li>
                  A <strong>category breakdown</strong> showing which areas
                  dominate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  A qualitative rating (e.g. “below global average”, “typical
                  high-income footprint”).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use these results to identify
                <strong>high-impact changes</strong>. For example, if flights
                account for 40% of your footprint, reducing air travel will
                matter more than small changes in lighting.
              </p>

              <h2>High-impact ways to reduce your carbon footprint</h2>
              <p>
                Research consistently shows that a small number of actions
                account for most of the potential reduction in an individual’s
                footprint. Here are some of the most effective levers, aligned
                with the categories in this calculator:
              </p>

              <h3>Home energy</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Improve insulation, seal drafts, and upgrade windows to reduce
                  heating and cooling demand.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Switch to a <strong>heat pump</strong> or high-efficiency
                  boiler where feasible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose a <strong>renewable electricity tariff</strong> or
                  install rooftop solar if possible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Replace old appliances with
                  <strong>high-efficiency models</strong> (fridge, HVAC, water
                  heater).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Transport & travel</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Drive less: combine trips, carpool, use public transit, bike,
                  or walk when practical.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose a more efficient car or switch to an
                  <strong>electric vehicle</strong> where the grid is relatively
                  clean.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fly less, especially long-haul. Consider trains or video calls
                  instead of frequent flights.
                </li>
                <li>
                  When you must fly, stay longer instead of multiple short
                  trips, and choose economy class (lower emissions per
                  passenger).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Food & diet</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Shift towards a <strong>more plant-based diet</strong>,
                  reducing red meat and dairy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cut <strong>food waste</strong> by planning meals, storing
                  food properly, and using leftovers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Favor seasonal, locally appropriate produce when it makes
                  sense.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Goods, services & lifestyle</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Buy <strong>fewer, higher-quality items</strong> that last
                  longer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Repair, reuse, and share (libraries, tool libraries,
                  second-hand markets) instead of always buying new.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider the footprint of digital services (streaming, cloud
                  storage) and enable energy-saving settings.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and data sources</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed as an
                <strong>educational tool</strong>, not a full life-cycle
                assessment. It uses emission factors and benchmarks inspired by
                sources such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  IPCC Assessment Reports and national greenhouse gas
                  inventories.
                </li>
                <li>
                  US EPA and EU environment agency emission factors for fuels
                  and electricity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Peer-reviewed life-cycle analyses of diets, transport modes,
                  and consumer goods.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Actual emissions vary by country, utility provider, vehicle
                model, and personal habits. For decisions that require precise
                accounting (e.g. corporate reporting, offsetting programs), use
                specialized tools and, where appropriate, consult a
                sustainability professional.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Carbon footprint FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is a carbon footprint?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    A carbon footprint is the total amount of greenhouse gases
                    emitted directly and indirectly by an individual,
                    organization, product, or activity, usually expressed in
                    tons of CO₂ equivalent (tCO₂e) per year. It includes
                    emissions from energy use, transport, food, goods, and
                    services across the full life cycle where possible.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is a typical carbon footprint per person?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Globally, the average per-person footprint is around 4–5
                    tCO₂e per year. In many high-income countries it is 10–20
                    tCO₂e, while in low-income countries it can be below 2
                    tCO₂e. To align with climate goals (around 1.5–2 °C of
                    warming), average per-person emissions would need to fall to
                    roughly 2 tCO₂e or less by mid-century.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is this calculator?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The calculator uses reasonable emission factors and typical
                    values, but it is still an approximation. It is most useful
                    for understanding orders of magnitude, comparing categories,
                    and identifying high-impact changes. For precise reporting
                    (e.g. corporate inventories), more detailed data and
                    methodologies are required.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Do carbon offsets reduce my footprint?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Offsets fund projects that reduce or remove emissions
                    elsewhere (such as reforestation or renewable energy). They
                    do not directly reduce your own emissions, but they can
                    compensate for them if the projects are high quality and
                    additional. Most experts recommend focusing first on
                    <strong>direct reductions</strong> (efficiency, behavior
                    change, clean energy) and using offsets for the remainder
                    you cannot yet avoid.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-4 py-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Why are flights and meat often so important?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Long-distance flights burn large amounts of fuel at high
                    altitude, where their warming impact is amplified. Red meat,
                    especially beef and lamb, has high emissions due to methane
                    from digestion, feed production, and land-use change. For
                    many people in high-income countries, these two areas can
                    dominate their personal footprint.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
